From fc7b3c32b89f24318a3549e59945c3219fc722f6 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Shane Williams <44717004+KingHavok@users.noreply.github.com>
Date: Sun, 21 Jun 2026 10:24:44 +1000
Subject: [PATCH] Support external authentication providers in front of Home
 Assistant

Keep main-frame authentication-provider navigation inside the WebView so
that OIDC / OAuth 2.0 reverse proxies (Cloudflare Access, Authelia,
Authentik, Vouch, oauth2-proxy) can complete their interactive sign-in
inside the app instead of being ejected to the system browser, which
breaks the flow because the resulting session cookie never returns to the
app's WebView.

Two signals keep navigation in-WebView: server-initiated http(s) redirects
on the main frame (the proxy challenge and its return redirect), and any
main-frame http(s) navigation while the WebView is currently on a host
other than the configured Home Assistant origin (so federated-IdP buttons
on a proxy login page are not ejected mid-flow). User-tapped external links
from the HA frontend are unaffected and still open in the system browser.

TLSWebViewClient gains a serverHost anchor set by WebViewActivity (on every
server load) and ConnectionViewModel (onboarding). getWebViewClient() is
API 26+, so WebViewActivity keeps its own reference to the client.

Known limitation: Google / Microsoft federated sign-in refuses to render in
any embedded WebView (Error 403: disallowed_useragent) by published
provider policy; use a non-federated factor (email OTP, TOTP, WebAuthn) or a
self-hosted IdP.

Based on closed upstream PR home-assistant/android#6725.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>
